  "business_context": "Volunteer Hour records track the unpaid labor that powers most nonprofits. They drive volunteer-recognition workflows (milestones for 100, 500, 1000 lifetime hours), grant-application reporting (many funders require evidence of volunteer engagement), tax documentation (the IRS doesn't allow valuation of volunteer time as a charitable deduction, but in-kind professional services can be tracked separately), and program-impact reporting (X volunteers contributed Y hours to deliver Z programs). Modeling varies considerably: NPSP has a Volunteer Hours object via the Volunteers for Salesforce extension (V4S — a separately-installed managed package); CiviCRM has a CiviVolunteer extension; Bloomerang has Volunteer hours as a built-in Interaction subtype with hours and project tracking; standard Salesforce, HubSpot, Attio, and EspoCRM have no native concept and require custom build-out. Hours are typically logged against a Project / Program / Event / Activity, with a contact (the volunteer), a date, hours count, and optional descriptive notes. When interviewing clients, surface \"Volunteer Hour\" by asking whether they engage volunteers, whether they need to track contributed hours for reporting or recognition, and whether volunteer hours roll up into program impact metrics.",
